==English==
===Etymology===
Middle English ''[[charme]]'' ([[chant]], [[magic spell]])< Old French< {{L.}} ''[[carmen]]'' ([[song]], [[incantation]])
=== Noun ===
'''charm''' ([[charms]])

#a small metallic [[trinket]] on a [[bracelet]] etc.
#:''She wears a '''charm''' bracelet on her [[wrist]].''
#an object, act or words believed to have magic power
#:''A '''charm''' against [[evil]]''
#:''It works like a '''charm'''.''
#a quality of delighting, arousing [[admiration]]
#:''She had great personal '''charm'''.''
#(physics) a property of some subatomic particles.
====Antonyms====
* (''quality of delighting''): [[boredom]]
